*doing business as*

**AERO RECORDS**

**Comprehensive Business Plan**

Aircraft Records Digitization Services

Kerrville, Texas (KERV / Louis Schreiner Field)

Executive Summary

Provenarc Group LLC, operating as Provenarc Aero Solutions, targets a \$50--55
million national annual market for aircraft records digitization---a
niche where aviation-grade document scanning commands a 10--50x price
premium over commodity scanning because the documents directly underpin
six- and seven-figure asset values. With startup capital of
approximately \$12,000, a solo operator working from Kerrville can reach
\$72,000--\$120,000 in Year 1 revenue at gross margins exceeding 80%,
achieving profitability from Month 1 of active operations.

The business occupies a defensible gap that no national competitor
fills: a concierge-model, white-glove scanning service rooted in the
physical ecosystem of the Texas Hill Country\'s uniquely concentrated
aviation corridor---where Mooney International\'s factory, Plane + Pilot
Dugosh Aviation\'s 40-year maintenance franchise, and a high-net-worth
turbine-owner population in the Boerne-San Antonio corridor converge
within a 70-mile radius.

This business plan provides specific pricing intelligence, a 14-tier
service menu, a three-year financial model, and an actionable
go-to-market playbook suitable for presenting to investors, SBA
microloan intermediaries, and strategic partners.

AREA 1: Competitive Landscape and Market Sizing

Six Competitors and Where They Leave the Door Open

The aircraft records digitization space has consolidated around a
handful of players, each with a distinct model---and each with
exploitable weaknesses for a locally embedded operator.

Vault Aircraft Records (Franklin, TN)

Vault Aircraft Records charges a flat \$920 starting fee for one-time
digital conversion plus \$89/month for physical storage in a bank-grade
concrete vault with Pelican AIR cases. Their product is premium and
defensible, but they require clients to deliver records to Tennessee or
ship via FedEx Custom Critical (dedicated vehicle). They explicitly
discourage standard shipping. No on-site scanning exists. No per-page
transparency. No local presence anywhere in Texas.

Bluetail (Scottsdale, AZ)

Bluetail is the market\'s 800-pound gorilla: an INC 5000 company (#309)
with 120+ scanning center locations, AI-powered MACH search, and pricing
tiered by aircraft complexity---\$75/month per aircraft for piston,
\$150/month for light jets, scaling to \$300/month for heavy jets, plus
setup fees of \$299--\$599. Scanning is quote-based through a
crowdsourced network of A&P mechanics and aviation professionals or
through SOC 2/HIPAA-compliant local scan centers. Bluetail\'s strength
is enterprise fleet management and Part 135 compliance workflows. Their
weakness: opaque scanning costs, no particular focus on the GA piston
owner-flyer segment, and no Central Texas scanning representative
currently identified in the Hill Country.

PlaneLogix (Carrboro, NC)

PlaneLogix occupies the GA-friendly end of the market with transparent
subscription pricing---\$6.95/month for self-service, \$129.95/year for
full-feature tracking. Their concierge scanning service (ship physical
logbooks to North Carolina) carries custom pricing. PlaneLogix recently
won a 545-aircraft Civil Air Patrol fleet contract and operates a formal
referral partner program where FBOs, maintenance shops, and
entrepreneurs earn commissions on sign-ups. Their gap: no local
presence, no on-site scanning capability, and the requirement to ship
irreplaceable logbooks across the country.

Vision Aircraft Records (Reno, NV)

Vision Aircraft Records claims to be the \"industry standard\" for
legacy record scanning, charging \$99/month per aircraft for their
S.M.A.R.T. platform. They partner with ARC Document Solutions for a
national on-site scanning network and claim to be the only provider
whose clients have had paperless recordkeeping systems formally accepted
by the FAA. Their focus skews heavily toward business jets and corporate
fleets---not the owner-flown Mooney at KERV.

SierraTrax (Wichita, KS)

SierraTrax launched a nationwide scanning network in 2021 and is the
Textron Aviation--recommended provider. Pricing runs approximately
\$199--\$499/year for maintenance tracking with scanning as an add-on.
Their focus on Textron products (Cessna, Beechcraft) is strong, but they
have no Hill Country presence.

The Gap That Defines Provenarc Aero Solutions\' Opportunity

No competitor offers all five of the following simultaneously: (1)
physical concierge pickup and return within the Hill Country, (2)
Mooney-specific airframe expertise and keyword indexing, (3) on-site
scanning at fly-in events, (4) 8130-3 form AI extraction with parts
traceability database output, and (5) transparent flat-rate pricing
without mandatory SaaS subscriptions. Provenarc Aero Solutions fills every one of
these gaps.

How Aviation Scanning Compares to Other Industries

The premium commanded by aviation document scanning is extraordinary.
General bulk document scanning runs \$0.05--\$0.12 per page. Fragile or
special-handling documents cost \$0.25/page. Medical records scanning in
regulated environments costs \$0.20--\$1.07/page depending on state fee
caps. Legal document scanning falls in the \$0.07--\$0.25/page range
with chain-of-custody premiums.

Aircraft maintenance record digitization, by contrast, effectively costs
\$1.50--\$5.00+ per page when flat fees are divided by typical page
counts---representing a 15--50x premium over commodity scanning. This
premium is justified by three factors: the irreplaceability of the
source documents (a lost logbook can destroy \$45,000--\$90,000 in asset
value), the aviation-specific expertise required to index and organize
records correctly, and the bailee liability assumed by the scanning
provider.

Total Addressable Market: The Numbers

The national active GA fleet comprises approximately 204,000--220,000
aircraft based on FAA CY2023 General Aviation Survey data extrapolated
at the FAA Aerospace Forecast\'s 0.6% annual growth rate. The fleet
breaks down to roughly 126,000--130,000 single-engine piston (58%),
12,000--13,000 multi-engine piston (6%), 10,500--11,500 turboprops (5%),
16,000--17,000 turbojets (7%), 10,800--11,200 rotorcraft (5%), and
32,000--34,000 experimental/homebuilt (15%).

Texas hosts approximately 28,174 registered aircraft---either the first
or second largest state fleet depending on the data source and
methodology. Applying the national active-to-registered ratio of 75--80%
yields roughly 21,000--22,000 active GA aircraft in Texas.

